text: pad lambda function tries to convert the privateInfo string into a string of length which is a perfect multiple of BLOCK_SIZE by padding the character stored in PADDING variable.  That is, if length of privateInfo string (let's say string is 'this is a private and confidential message and must not be read by any third party. not even a government official with highest level of security clearance') is 155 bytes, with the BLOCK_SIZE 16, the string will be transformed to 'this is a private and confidential message and must not be read by any third party. not even a government official with highest level of security clearance{{{{{' of length 160 bytes.

text: problem in installation  win10 and python3.6  The file include\pyport.h in Python installation directory does not have #include < stdint.h > anymore. This leaves intmax_t undefined.  A workaround for Microsoft VC compiler is to force include stdint.h via OS environment variable CL:  Open command prompt with admin privileges Run vsvars32.bat from your version of VC set CL=-FI"%VCINSTALLDIR%\INCLUDE\stdint.h" pip install pycrypto   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41843266/microsoft-windows-python-3-6-pycrypto-installation-error

author: @temetnoscesemper
text: Don't know if it was already answered but there are a few encryption modes that exist within symmetric encryption suites. The one your using is in "block" mode, meaning that each message block has to be a certain length (usually something along the the lines of 32, 64, or 128 bits). The padding just ensures that the string is atleast some multiple of that number.  Stream ciphers on the other hand, don't require this. Each mode has it's own pro's and cons.
